result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

9:29 AM Defendant Khirsten E Phalen in court.  Attorney William George Weiland in court for Khirsten E Phalen.  Attorney Jedidiah J Dodge in court for State of Wisconsin. 
Cases heard at this time are: 22CM-163, 22CF-302, 21CM,127 and 21CF-181. 

Court calls cases.
Atty Dodge states appearances.

Plea Questionnaire/Agreement filed.
Prosecutor states plea agreement.
22CM-163 needs an initial appearance.
Defendant will plead to Count 1 in 21CF-181. All other counts and files will be dismissed and read in.
Attorney for defendant concurs with agreement stated.
Defendant concurs.

State never filed an information in 21CF-181.
Atty Dodge will file an information right now. 
Defendant does not want to proceed without the information.
Court states the information will be the same as the complaint.
Defendant states she would like to proceed without it.

Defendant enters a plea of: 
21CF-181: Count 1: No Contest.

State has complied with Victim Notification Statutes in some of these cases.
Victim is not present.

Court questions defendant regarding plea questionnaire, waiver of constitutional rights and understandings.
Court advises defendant of elements the state must prove for the charge.
Court questions attorney for the defendant.
Court finds defendant's plea is freely, voluntarily, knowingly, and intelligently made.
Attorneys stipulate that there is factual basis for the charge.

BY THE COURT:
Court finds a sufficient factual basis to support the charge.
Court finds the defendant guilty of Count 1 in 21CF-181.
Clerk directed to enter judgment of conviction this date.
22CM-163: Dismissed and read in.
22CF-302: Dismissed and read in.
21CM-127: Dismissed and read in. 

Atty Dodge makes sentencing arguments to the court. 
Atty Weiland makes sentencing arguments to the court, this is a joint recommendation.

Court has a number of factors to consider to determine sentencing.

BY THE COURT: 
21CF-181:
Count 1:
Jail sentence for 180 days.
With huber for work or school or anything the Jail deems appropriate.
Imposed and Stayed.
Probation for a period of 3 years.
